#: ../../install/ssl.rst:18
msgid "SSL configuration"
msgstr ""

#: ../../install/ssl.rst:19
msgid ""
"Murano components are able to work with SSL. This chapter will help your to "
"make proper settings with SSL configuration."
msgstr ""

#: ../../install/ssl.rst:23
msgid "HTTPS for Murano API"
msgstr ""

#: ../../install/ssl.rst:25
msgid ""
"SSL for Murano API service can be configured in *ssl* section in "
"``/etc/murano/murano.conf``. Just point to a valid SSL certificate. See the "
"example below:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../install/ssl.rst:37
msgid ""
"*cert\\_file*    Path to the certificate file the server should use when "
"binding to an SSL-wrapped socket."
msgstr ""

#: ../../install/ssl.rst:38
msgid ""
"*key\\_file*     Path to the private key file the server should use when "
"binding to an SSL-wrapped socket."
msgstr ""

#: ../../install/ssl.rst:39
msgid ""
"*ca\\_file*      Path to the CA certificate file the server should use to "
"validate client certificates provided during an SSL handshake. This is "
"ignored if cert\\_file and \"key\\_file\" are not set."
msgstr ""

#: ../../install/ssl.rst:41
msgid ""
"The use of SSL is automatically started after point to HTTPS protocol "
"instead of HTTP during registration Murano API service in endpoints (Change "
"publicurl argument to start with \\https://). SSL for Murano API is "
"implemented like in any other OpenStack component. This realization is based"
" on ssl python module so more information about it can be found `here`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../install/ssl.rst:51
msgid "SSL for RabbitMQ"
msgstr ""

#: ../../install/ssl.rst:53
msgid ""
"All Murano components communicate with each other by RabbitMQ. This "
"interaction can be encrypted with SSL. By default all messages in Rabbit MQ "
"are not encrypted. Each RabbitMQ Exchange should be configured separately."
msgstr ""

#: ../../install/ssl.rst:58
msgid "**Murano API <-> Rabbit MQ exchange <-> Murano Engine**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../install/ssl.rst:60
msgid ""
"Edit ssl parameters in default section of ``/etc/murano/murano.conf``. Set "
"``rabbit_use_ssl`` option to *true* and configure ssl kombu parameters. "
"Specify the path to the SSL keyfile and SSL CA certificate in a regular "
"format: /path/to/file without quotes or leave it empty to allow self-signed "
"certificates."
msgstr ""

#: ../../install/ssl.rst:85
msgid "**Murano Agent -> Rabbit MQ exchange**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../install/ssl.rst:87
msgid ""
"In main murano configuration file there is a section ,named *rabbitmq*, that"
" is responsible for set up communication between Murano Agent and Rabbit MQ."
" Just set *ssl* parameter to True to enable ssl."
msgstr ""

#: ../../install/ssl.rst:100
msgid ""
"If you want to configure Murano Agent in a different way change the default "
"template. It can be found in Murano Core Library, located at "
"*http://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack/murano/tree/meta/io.murano/Resources/Agent-v1.template*."
" Take a look at appSettings section:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../install/ssl.rst:124
msgid ""
"Desired parameter should be set directly to the value of the key that you "
"want to change. Quotes are need to be kept. Thus you can change "
"\"rabbitmq.ssl\" and \"rabbitmq.port\" values to make Rabbit MQ work with "
"this exchange in a different from Murano-Engine way. After modification, "
"don't forget to zip and re-upload core library."
msgstr ""

#: ../../install/ssl.rst:131
msgid "SSL for Murano Dashboard"
msgstr ""

#: ../../install/ssl.rst:133
msgid ""
"If you are going not to use self-signed certificates additional "
"configuration do not need to be done. Just point https in the URL. "
"Otherwise, set *MURANO_API_INSECURE = True* on horizon config. You can find "
"it in ``/etc/openstack-dashboard/local_settings.py.``."
msgstr ""
